The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Shillong, May 13: A seven-member Meghalaya United Alliance ministry, led by Congress Legislature Party leader D.D. Lapang, was sworn in on Wednesday, ending nearly two months of Presidents rule in the state.           Lapang was sworn in as chief minister. A non-legislator, Ampareen Lyngdoh, was also inducted in the ministry.                  
	Bhubaneswar (PTI): B.B. Mohanty, Orissas top police officer, reported for duty on Wednesday, a day after the state government revoked his 20-month suspension. Mohanty was suspended after a court issued a non-bailable warrant against him in 2007, on the charge of helping his rape convict son Bitihotra jump parole from jail.                  
	Kozhikode (PTI): A Gulf-bound passenger, whose luggage went missing on May 6 after screening at the airport here, has sought compensation from authorities for negligence in duty. Moroly Ali, who failed to board the flight and said he might lose his job because of the negligence, got back his luggage on Tuesday but found some valuable items missing.                   
	 Bangalore (PTI): Anti-American Imperialism Forum members, protesting US President Barack Obamas Bangalore to Buffalo remark, were arrested when they tried to forcibly enter Bank Of America premises shouting slogans. Obama had recently said incentives would be given to BPO companies for creating jobs inside the US, in places like Buffalo City, rather than outsourcing them.                  
	Port Blair (PTI): Police have arrested a tantrik for allegedly molesting a 12-year-old girl at Diglipur in Andaman and Nicobar Islands.
                                                                                                                           
